LayoutNode.Content: About a week ago, I went to a wedding reception. I've actuallynever heard of this venue, but I had the chance to check it out onFriday, January 19th around 6:15pm. I believe the front bar area more or less remains the same. Theywere offering beer and wine at $8 a pop. Not sure if the beer isworth it, but the glasses of wine were very generous pours. Afterthat initial area, I think you can do anything you want with thespace. They turned the room past into the main dining area with along dinner table, dessert table, and the dj. There was a smallroom to the left that they turned into a coat check. And a loft stylesecond level where they did the toasts and made announcements.Past that, there's one more room in the back which they turnedinto the kid area and buffet. The only thing lacking is restrooms. Ibelieve there are only two, so there was a lot of waiting if youwanted to use the bathroom. And believe me, with all the drinking,I needed to go. A lot! There seems to be a downstairs, but it wasroped off, so we didn't have access to it. Very cool space. The front area has a cafe type feel, but the restcan be transformed into anything you want. I especially liked theloft type area. Seemed very cute and cozy. Depending on yourvision, I think The Laundry could be a good venue. I definitely hada great time for the 4+ hours we were here. Great for a smallinformal wedding reception.

LayoutNode.Content: I live a few blocks away and frequently pass by the Laundry. Fromthe outside, I assumed it was a cafe that allowed for hanging outand drinking coffee, and from the website I gathered that they hostthe occasional art event. Today I had some time to kill so I decidedto try it out. I walked into the "pop-up" cafe expecting a place todrink coffee, sit and get some work done, and maybe look at someart. When I walked in, the person taking orders was busy lookingat his phone and didn't acknowledge me. After a moment theperson in the barista position asked me what I wanted and took myorder. Looking past the cafe bar I saw a room full of people sittingat a big desk behind glass doors. I asked if that was cafe seatingand was informed that it was being used for a "corporate event".Ewww. So, I took my drink (Gibraltar with slightly over-extracted espresso) to a small corner chair and signed into the guest wifi as directed.The wifi was very slow and kept dropping out. Reading otherreviews on Yelp it appears that there is a very fast connectionavailable... if you reserve the workspace in the back. I'm sad. What I had hoped was a cafe and community art spacehas turned out to be just another tech/corporate sharedworkspace. Another nail in the coffin of the Mission.

LayoutNode.Content: Awesome versatile venue in a beautiful industrial space; a realneighborhood gem! It's hard to describe The Laundry in a fewwords, given how eclectic it is -- great craft coffee at the pop-upcafe in the morning, super fast Internet in the coworking space toget work done, and an excellent cultural events program in theevenings, ranging from live music (check out theAirbnb-sponsored events) and stand-up comedy, to art shows andsocial justice events such as the recent "I Am An Immigrant"campaign. One of my favorite spots in SF (if only the coffee shopwere open on weekends, it would be perfect).

LayoutNode.Content: I rented this space during the day on the weekend to host aprivate brunch party for about 40-50 people. It was a wonderfulexperience for all my guests and we really enjoyed the layout ofspace. We rented the upstairs main room and there was also afabulous art show in the back gallery area we got to enjoy. The tealounge landing and sofa seating area were great for inspiringconversations. I really like how all the tables had sturdy reclaimedwood tops on wheels. It made it easy for us to move the tablesaround and we changed the space into a dance floor towards theend of the event. The skylights made the space light filledthroughout the day and the eclectic industrial interior design madethe event a successful experience. Cynthia the manager was greatto work with too! She offered clear communication and was easy towork with. I would highly recommend holding events here for yourworkshops, parties, or dining events! I became aware of The Laundry at one of their art show openings.Once I saw the space I had to become a member. So I also usethis space to hang out in, read, and work on my passion duringthe weekday. Again I love the light filled main room and the vibe isgreat between all the other members sharing the space. I also loveall the classes they offer to members which are mostly free, likeyoga. Every week they hold workshops or a class which are feebased that are great for helping you to develop your businessconcepts and inspire your visions into reality. The co-founders aregreat too. I'm happy to support people with a vision that buildscommunity, inspires art and cultivates innovative ideas. Check outtheir event page to stay updated and come support this wonderfulspace in the mission.

This Venue is truly amazing. I first found the Laundry when I attended a yoga class that was accompanied by cellists! Since then The Laundry has become my favorite place in San Francisco, from working out of the cafe to attending art exhibitions, The Laundry has fostered a creative, upbeat community that welcomes all. I threw my first private event at the Laundry last week and it was perfect! Katie and the staff are amazing to work with and are extremely professional. I would highly recommend The Laundry for ANY event or activity you have planned.
